author: @gerardojg
text: After watching this movie and hearing how horrible it is, I think there were great ideas but poorly executed. What works is the dynamics between Cassie, Anya, Mattie, and Julia, mostly. It could have carried the movie. They put the cart before the horse, sequels. The biggest error is trying to spin the birth of Peter Parker into the plot, 20-30 minutes of screen time wasted. The lead protagonist origin story was a great idea to include reconciliation with her mother. Another big error, they should've given the girls their powers to solidify their bond with one another. It would've made the final act more satisfying. The villain was poorly written, and his motives were never clearly defined. Was it world domination, genocide, or enslavement of the human race?  Yes, he wanted to kill the girls but why would they kill him. A question never put forward and not answered. The design and development of Madam Webb's precognition was terrible. It could've worked but I will not deny my suggestions would cost money. I'm willing to bet that a complete script didn't exist before shooting started. Multiple changes occurred as shooting was done. That costs more than my suggestions during development.

author: @nikitaantonov7831
text:
"Veiling the Mind's Eye: Madame Web's Odyssey into the Unseen"

Embarking on Stardew Valley, I anticipated a straightforward journey of pastoral simplicity. Yet, beneath its unassuming surface, a narrative as convoluted and enigmatic as the darkest cinematic mysteries began to unfold. In Pelican Town, every planted seed and nurtured relationship spiraled into a narrative labyrinth, challenging my perceptions of reality, much like the complex webs of deception and illusion one might expect from Madame Web. However, where Madame Web tangled itself in its own ambitious plot, Stardew Valley masterfully wove a tale of profound depth and intrigue.

The daily rituals of this virtual Eden masked a deeper exploration of existence, where the ordinary transformed into the extraordinary. The townspeople, with their myriad secrets and desires, mirrored the complex characters of a psychological thriller, drawing me deeper into a story where truth flickered like a shadow, elusive and ever-changing. This journey through Stardew Valley, with its shifting realities and hidden depths, paralleled the twisted narratives found in tales of intrigue and mystery, where nothing is as it seems, and every revelation leads only to more questions.

Stardew Valley's serene fa√ßade belied a complex exploration of the human psyche, turning each in-game day into a step deeper into both the valley's and my own subconscious. Here, the boundaries between game and reality blurred, each discovery a piece of a puzzle that, when pieced together, revealed a picture far different from what I had initially perceived. This game became a reflection of the intricate dance between perception and reality, where Madame Web's attempt at a multifaceted narrative paled in comparison to the genuine depth and complexity Stardew Valley offered.

As I delved deeper into the heart of Pelican Town, I found a community of players whose shared experiences echoed the collective journey through our own psychological mazes. This communal narrative, rich with individual stories of discovery and revelation, underscored the profound impact of Stardew Valley. It became clear that this was not just a game, but a journey into the unknown, challenging us to question our understanding of reality, much like the protagonists of the most bewildering psychological thrillers.

In this digital idyll, Stardew Valley emerged not merely as a game but as an enigmatic masterpiece, ensnaring players in a narrative web as intricate and unpredictable as the plot twists of Madame Web, yet with the depth and coherence the film aspired to but ultimately failed to achieve. In the end, Stardew Valley revealed itself to be a mirror, reflecting the complexities of the mind and the elusive nature of truth, far outshining the tangled narrative of Madame Web with its serene yet profoundly deceptive storytelling.

author: @enjoyyourself7455
text:
Nic Cage did it better in Next...
Sony really dropped the ball by not utilising Venom to really establish their connected universe. They could've (maybe should've) had Madame Webb recruiting Venom as a guardian to protect the 3 of them (or preferably other possible characters). That would've also allowed them to explain his connection to Spiderman without their characters interacting.
However, pushing this a one dimensional, self-contained movie left it with no reason for viewers, even fans, to invest or connect with the characters or plot. It's a genuine shame too because the action scenes were some of the best Spiderman inspired action sequences I've seen in live action wasted on an origin story NOBODY asked for or wanted with a plot that's too obvious to be so convoluted. With way too many characters playing at comic relief.
They could've finally found a simple way to write out his love interest and give them both a uniting redemption arc saving these three characters with Madame Webb instead coming back to orchestrate it and lead the action to them three and Venom until stepping in at the end instead. Otherwise, everything else was way too obvious with that prediction plotline.

author: @aastikkhatri5643
text:
Somewhere on this earth, sitting in his room a Sony executive scrolling down and reading all the comments on Madame Web Trailer, each time he scrolls the more perplexed he gets.

Seeing her husband in this state his wife asks "honey what happened ?"

Still with a puzzled expression on his face, the husband replied "I don't know what went wrong honey, all these comments are praising the movie and quoting it but still it didn't make any profit."

His wife worried "I think you should give it a rest and sleep It's already 2 am"

Ignoring his wife's suggestion the man continues scrolling hoping to change something but neither the comments changed nor the box office collection. Then suddenly his finger stopped and he moved away his eyes from the brightness of his phone. Looking at the ceiling his expression started to change from a state of bewilderment to excitement, an idea has popped in his mind and with this new refined confidence, he looked at his phone again. Not to look at the comments but to phone someone at Sony HQ.

Someone picked up on the other end
"It's 3 am what so important that couldn't wait for tomorrow"

The man still thrilled replied-


"What If we release it a 2nd time"

author: @omfgjflo
text:
Why are "dude" films successful? Because us dudes know we're the best things since sliced bread and we dont advertise that we are dudes, we just embody what we already know.
why am i saying that?
well i'll use a very good example.
There's a show called "Suits". Awesome show. Whole cast is awesome with some really strong female roles but we all know who the character is...."Harvey Spectre"
Now, every character has real strong potential to have their own spinoff, but they ought to know that a show Specifically about them wouldn't make for a strong show.
kind of a "don't stear too far from home" type thing.

but they did... one of the show's characters had a spinoff. Now, she's one of my favorite characters of the show. However, the problem they had was naming it "Pearson".
After the character. however, what does that say to an audience that doesn't know anything about the show.
"PC girl power."
Only a single familiar character for old fans, and no traction for new fans.

now with madame web..... She's a seriously unknown character, with only real spiderman fans knowing her.
keyword "spiderman fans".
Spidermans villains or supporting characters are not much without spiderman.
Venom is the only exception.
The fact sony thought this would be a strong movie without spiderman and then went Girlpower is ridiculous.

if you're a BAMF, you dont have to tell the world you are, they'll already know it.

author: @DarkFox2232
text:
Great Story:
- Spuuder Guy wants to kill 3 teenage girls, because his attempt on killing them will later turn them into spuuder girls... who will... kill him.
- But attempt is "interrupted" by 4th, just-in-time awakened, spuuder woman who literally just walks them away as Spuuder Guy effortlessly annihilates cops instead of girls.
- Spuuder Woman is accused of kidnapping those 3 girls as reward. And that's her reason to actually kidnap them with words: "This is still not kidnapping."
-=> This is all there is to 1st half of movie.
- Hide in the forest. Have pointlessly dumb conversations while saying: "Just stay here. Don't do anything dumb." Followed by Spuuder Woman attempting dumb things.
- Girls abduction is on front page of magazine within hours. Girls walk into only gas station on planet where hillbillies read newspaper.
- Hillbilly assumes that random girls who show no sign of distress are ones kidnapped and reports them. Then continues to sit at the bar as nothing is wrong while girls dance on table. (Not even Drunk.)
- Instead of cops, Spuuder Guy gets there. And Spuuder Woman right after. Walking girls out uneventfully for 2nd time.
- Time for upgrade quest... as remote viewing, telepathy, precognition, ... was not enough.
- No new abilities were needed to effortlessly get away for 3rd time. Followed by intentionally creating mass destruction situation... possibly killing dozens to save three.
- Final confrontation... crawl on all four backwards till ex machina kills bad Spuuder guy.
- Followed by random & unforeseen drowning of Spuuder woman. As she gets deeper under water, she enjoys meteor shower which effortlessly pierces water. And she gets blinded by one meteor hitting her face without melting skin away in process.
-=> Paralysis from waist down is just bonus... to be closer to Madame Web one day... as if this had way to spawn another movie.


Great Dialogs:
- Spuuder woman after getting them out of harm's way for 1st time: "Your parents should take care of this."
- Not yet Spuuder girls: "Our parents are too busy to protect us in any way."

- Spuuder Guy: "You're just like your mother."
- Spuuder woman: "Yes, I am." -- while having very low opinion of her mother for all the years. And never meeting her since she died at childbirth.


Creativity:
- Spuuder Woman calls her cat: "Cat"
- Electro-shocking metal roof of medical car to shock Spuuder Guy above it. (I guess, his suit and himself are superconducting, have 0 Ohm resistance. Otherwise all current flows just in metal ceiling.)

author: @ClassyNugget
text:
"What do you want from me?"

"To be a good movie"

Honestly, this is a slap in the face for all Spider-man fans. It's how you do fan service even worse than you ever could. You spit in the face of Spider-man fans by doing literally everything related to him without mentioning or saying his name. Even the main villain is loosely named I kid you not "Guy who crawls on walls" "CEiling GUy" "Crawling Spider like guy". I think Sony just hates Spider-man. Given the very first Spider anything introduced has to be the main villain of the story & ngl costume is pretty cool but his motivation is understandable but also freakin weak at the same time. You never even see any Spider characters only in a vision , which I'm sure is the bait to see this trippy psychedelic psychological horror film of a movie. Not to mention how weak, unimaginative, & uncreative the spider designs are, 1 from trailer alone are Iron Spiders legs from Avengers Infinity War, in the costume of Spider-man 2099 suit with Jessica Drew's hair style from Spiderverse. Bro they copy pasted their own work with no originality. I can go on but I think its case in point. I could spoil the entire movie here but honestly the trailer does that because everything in it literally happens in the movie.

author: @gicousinjoe6199
text:
Pitchman: Picture this: "Madame Web" but with a twist so fresh, it makes farm-to-table look like fast food. Dakota Johnson is Cassie Webb, a paramedic turned psychic superhero, thanks to a Peruvian spider bite.

Producer: Wait, a psychic superhero based on a spider bite? Isn't that stretching the superhero genre a bit thin?

Pitchman: Stretching, or innovating? Imagine, if you will, a world where our hero doesn't just fight crime‚Äîshe sees it coming. It's like Minority Report meets Charlotte's Web, with a dash of Fast and Furious, because guess what? She drives an ambulance like it's a Lamborghini.

Producer: So, our hero's main talent is driving fast and seeing the future? That sounds... vaguely useful, I guess.

Pitchman: Vaguely useful? Please, I'm going to need you to get all the way off my back about this. Cassie's clairvoyance isn't just a party trick; it's the key to stopping crimes before they happen. Plus, she's got a tragic backstory with a jungle spider that could've cured cancer or something. It's emotionally charged, action-packed, and has just enough science to not make sense.

Producer: A jungle spider that could've cured cancer? And we're using this for superhero powers? That seems like a missed opportunity for, I don't know, actual healing?

Pitchman: Healing, schmealing. We're in the business of healing the soul with high-octane entertainment. And speaking of business, let's talk about the real villain of our story: geography. We've got scenes in Queens, New Jersey, and a Peruvian jungle by way of Canada. It's a multicultural rollercoaster of confusion and excitement.

Producer: That sounds like a logistical and narrative nightmare. How do you expect audiences to follow that?

Pitchman: Audiences love a good puzzle! And speaking of puzzles, let's talk about our protagonist's psychic abilities. They're not just visions; they're an immersive 4D experience that sometimes involves her doing CPR incorrectly as a metaphor for how we're all just trying to save ourselves.

Producer: Incorrect CPR as a metaphor? That's what we're going with? And how do we address the glaring issues with continuity and basic common sense?

Pitchman: Oh, I'll tell you how we address it: with flair. Continuity and common sense are so last century. We're breaking boundaries, pushing envelopes, and maybe breaking a few laws of physics while we're at it. And if that gets your producer panties in a bunch, well, I'm gonna need you to launch yourself off my back with a trebuchet.

Producer: Launch myself off... Fine. Let's pretend for a moment this all makes sense. What's our endgame here? Another tangled web in the Spider-Verse that leaves more questions than answers?

Pitchman: Exactly! It's not about the destination; it's about the spectacular, web-slinging journey. And just when you think it couldn't get any more convoluted, we throw in a plot twist so unexpected, it makes M. Night Shyamalan look predictable.

Producer: I'm almost afraid to ask, but what's the twist?

Pitchman: The twist is that the real superpower was the friends we made along the way. And by friends, I mean contractual obligations to keep churning out Spider-Man content. It's a heartwarming tale of legal strategy and corporate synergy.

Producer: Heartwarming? More like heartburn-inducing. But fine, let's spin this web. After all, what's the worst that could happen? We've already set the bar so low, a limbo dancer couldn't get under it.

Pitchman: That's the spirit! With enough low bars, we'll start a limbo party that everyone's invited to. "Madame Web": Coming soon to a theater near you, whether you like it or not!

text:
The now vapid movie industry still paying Google/Youtube for it's own "likes" I see...why is the whole world now just empty, souless and cringeworthy? And why is every single character in every single movie now, no-matter what it is or what the style etc, always just fresh-faced and wearing brand new t shirts and jeans...?? It's like they've actually full on forgotten how to make films at this point. Just get a bunch of kids who've no idea how to act beyond the school plays they've just come from, dress them off the rack in t shirts and jeans and then film them doing random action scenes on a green set. Give the movie to some other kids with laptops to finish everything else, brand it, market it and sell it as a Hollywood blockbuster.

I really REALLY miss when I was growing up and every single year you went to the cinema and saw amazing movies like Alien, ET, Blade Runner, The Terminator, Predator, Back to the Future, Home Alone, Pulp Fiction, Jurassic Park, Men in Black... those were just a few, literally every single year there was at least one masterpiece that's still revered and used to spin franchises today.

author: @raaaamirezzz
text:
I love the part when Henry comes out of no where and says,

‚ÄúConnection terminated.
I'm sorry to interrupt you, Elizabeth.
If you still even remember that name.
But I'm afraid you've been misinformed.
You are not here to receive a gift.
Nor, have you been called here by the individual you assume.
Although, you have indeed been called.

You have all been called here.
Into a labyrinth of sounds and smells, misdirection and misfortune.
A labyrinth with no exit, a maze with no prize.
You don't even realize that you are trapped.
Your lust of blood has driven you in endless circles.
Chasing the cries of children in some unseen chamber.
Always seeming so near, yet somehow out of reach.
But, you will never find them, none of you will.
This is where your story ends.

And to you, my brave volunteer.
Who somehow found this job listing not intended for you.
Although, there was a way out planned for you,
I have a feeling that's not what you want.
I have a feeling that you are right where you want to be.

I am remaining as well. I am nearby.
This place will not be remembered.
And the memory of everything that started this.
Can finally begin to fade away.
As the agony of every tragedy should.
And to you monsters trapped in the corridors.
Be still, and give up your spirits.
They don't belong to you.
For most of you, I believe there is peace and perhaps, warm.
Waiting for you after the smoke clears.
Although, for one of you.
The darkest pit of Hell has opened to swallow you whole.
So, don't keep the Devil waiting, old friend.

My daughter, if you can hear me.
I knew you would return as well.
It's in your nature to protect the innocent.
I'm sorry that on that day.
The day you were shut out and left to die.
No one was there to lift you up in their arms.
The way you lifted others into yours.
And then, what became of you?
I should have known, you wouldn't be content to disappear.
Not my daughter. I couldn't save you then, so let me save you now.
It's time to rest, for you, and for those you have carried in your arms.

This ends.
For all of us.
End communication.‚Äù

author: @DarkPhoenix203Ct
text: FFS who green lit this movie? It's garbage like this that is killing the comic book movie genre. Nobody wants to see random c and d class super heroes and villains the average person doesn't even know.  Why do you think Ant-Man flopped and the same with the marvels. Nobody cares about these characters unless you make ppl care and not having a movie the lays the ground work to introduce these character to ppl who've never heard of them is a recipe for failure. Fans wanna see the characters they know, not some off shoot character form the spiderman universe that nobody's cares about. The only comic book movies anyone cares about right now are Deadpool 3 and the X-Men. Ppl have been waiting yrs for these movies to comes out but marvel and sony think it makes more sense to make movies on characters barely anyone knows unless your an actual reader of the comics and know your stuff. But the worst part about that is these movie writers don't stick to what the comics did and totally change anything and everything that made these character what and who they are. For example the villain In this movie does t have the power to see the future just like Kamala Kahn in the marvels didn't have the powers they gave her since her actual power is the ability to stretch her body like Mr fantastic. Hollywood is killing the comic book movie genre  by doing this nonsense and the only way they will learn is by losing money but they've been losing money for a while now since the last few movies marvel did were god awful and so were all the Disney Plus shows they've done in the last 2yrs. Sony doesn't own rights to anything but Spiderman's universe but they choose to do this movie instead of a movie with characters like the sinister 6 who so many average ppl are familiar with.

text: I love it when she says, "Son, we live in a world that has walls, and those walls have to be guarded by men with guns. Who's gonna do it? You? You, Lieutenant Weinberg? I have a greater responsibility than you can possibly fathom. You weep for Santiago, and you curse the Marines. You have that luxury. You have the luxury of not knowing what I know -- that Santiago's death, while tragic, probably saved lives; and my existence, while grotesque and incomprehensible to you, saves lives.  You don't want the truth because deep down in places you don't talk about at parties, you want me on that wall -- you need me on that wall.  We use words like "honor," "code," "loyalty." We use these words as the backbone of a life spent defending something. You use them as a punch line.  I have neither the time nor the inclination to explain myself to a man who rises and sleeps under the blanket of the very freedom that I provide and then questions the manner in which I provide it.  I would rather that you just said "thank you" and went on your way. Otherwise, I suggest you pick up a weapon and stand the post. Either way, I don't give a DAMN what you think you're entitled to!"  Literally shaking right now.

What we didn‚Äôt know, was that our bomb mission was so secret, no distress signal had been sent. They didn‚Äôt even list us overdue for a week. Very first light, Chief, sharks come cruisin‚Äô by, so we formed ourselves into tight groups. It was sorta like you see in the calendars, you know the infantry squares in the old calendars like the Battle of Waterloo and the idea was the shark come to the nearest man, that man he starts poundin‚Äô and hollerin‚Äô and sometimes that shark he go away‚Ä¶ but sometimes he wouldn‚Äôt go away.
Sometimes that shark looks right at ya. Right into your eyes. And the thing about a shark is he‚Äôs got lifeless eyes. Black eyes. Like a doll‚Äôs eyes. When he comes at ya, he doesn‚Äôt even seem to be livin‚Äô‚Ä¶ ‚Äôtil he bites ya, and those black eyes roll over white and then‚Ä¶ ah then you hear that terrible high-pitched screamin‚Äô. The ocean turns red, and despite all your poundin‚Äô and your hollerin‚Äô those sharks come in and‚Ä¶ they rip you to pieces.
You know by the end of that first dawn, lost a hundred men. I don‚Äôt know how many sharks there were, maybe a thousand. I do know how many men, they averaged six an hour. Thursday mornin‚Äô, Chief, I bumped into a friend of mine, Herbie Robinson from Cleveland. Baseball player. Boson‚Äôs mate. I thought he was asleep. I reached over to wake him up. He bobbed up, down in the water, he was like a kinda top. Upended. Well, he‚Äôd been bitten in half below the waist.
At noon on the fifth day, a Lockheed Ventura swung in low and he spotted us, a young pilot, lot younger than Mr. Hooper here, anyway he spotted us and a few hours later a big ol‚Äô fat PBY come down and started to pick us up. You know that was the time I was most frightened. Waitin‚Äô for my turn. I‚Äôll never put on a lifejacket again. author: @jak71113
text: This was a reply I had to a comment, but it‚Äôs worth a general comment:  I saw ‚ÄúX-men,‚Äù which came out in 2000, in theatre (a girl I was dating at the time, was a big fan and wanted to see it.)  Ever since that film, Hollywood has been non-stop with these kind of films.  I prefer real sets/locations, along with practical special FX.  Today‚Äôs films, especially all of these comic book films, are mostly done in a studio with green screens all around them.  Heck, Warner Brother Ranch was recently torn down (the U-shaped ‚Äúneighborhood‚Äù in Burbank, CA, that has been the site of many TV shows and films, so they could build multiple sound stages on the property.)  Myself, and many others, are tired of the lazy Hollywood that can‚Äôt waste time putting together a ‚ÄúLord of the Rings‚Äù worthy film (meaning, filming at 150 locations, creating amazing sets/models, hundreds of ‚Äúenemies‚Äù with prosthetics/latex faces/masks and outfits.  Hollywood would rather pump out one cookie-cutter comic book film after another (and don‚Äôt forget the diversity/wokeness, tied to poor storylines.)

author: @notgonnahappen7899
text:
A 3 minute first trailer is a terrible sign. The more of a movie they show off before release, like The Flash, the worse it is.

Look at any good film. You start off with short teasers. Then a 1st and eventually 2nd trailer, each 2 minutes or less.

This isn't a character or story you can watch a movie about without knowing anything about them ahead of time. It's trading off it's loose Spider-Man connection without Spider-Man being involved in any way.

It's pandering, plain and simple. Instead of giving us a Black Cat or Spider-Gwen movie people would actually enjoy, we get D tier Madame Web. This movie with bomb, they will label fans sexist, and won't learn their lesson.

author: @CardamineLyrata
text:
The problem with the current standalone sony movies is that they try to make uniwue characters fit into the genre of an action thriller just because theyre from Marvel. What makes Marvel so unique is that it has such a wide range of characters with different tones, from street-level Luke Cage to omnipotent existential dread-level Living Tribunal.

The issue is that no matter the tone of the character, they always force them to become another average superhero action flick. That genre doesnt FIT madame web, morbius or kraven. Thats why these are going to flop really badly.

If youre going to have a new character, stop basing their legacy and milking the popular characters to clickbait your audience. Give the character its own unique movie with a unique genre. The reason daredevil worked so well was because it was such a refreshing palette cleanser, it didnt try to be your average avengers level threat superhero series. It explored a world on its own, it didnt rely on big names like Captain America to make an appearance to clickbait the audience into watching it - because it didnt need to. It was something unique, fresh, it was a dark and gritty tone that fit the character.

Morbius couldve been psychological horror, what makes the character so interesting is that he has an insatiable thirst for blood, but doesnt actually wanna kill. If youre gonna make a movie about him, play into the tone of the character and what makes him so interesting. Play into the horrifying mental problems that happen after you just realised you had sucked the blood out of someone. Play. Into. The character's tone.

Imagine if Madame Web was a psychological thriller, there would be so many interesting things that go on in your mind if you could look into the future, but sony ignores that and tries to make it into an action film once again. Ive said it before and I'll say it again, play. Into. The character's tone.

TLDR, Sony needs to expand their cinematic palette and stop morphing unique characters with unique tones and settings into another average superhero flick. They deserve more than that.

"Grass is a type of plant with narrow leaves growing from the base. Their appearance as a common plant was in the mid-Cretaceous period. There are 12,000 species now.[3]
A common kind of grass is used to cover the ground in places such as lawns and parks. Grass is usually the color green. That is because they are wind-pollinated rather than insect-pollinated, so they do not have to attract insects. Green is the best colour for photosynthesis.
Grasslands such as savannah and prairie where grasses are dominant cover 40.5% of the land area of the Earth, except Greenland and Antarctica.[4]
Grasses are monocotyledon herbaceous plants. They include the "grass" of the family Poaceae, which are called grass by ordinary people. This family is also called the Gramineae, and includes some of the sedges (Cyperaceae) and the rushes (Juncaceae).[5] These three families are not very closely related, though all of them belong to clades in the order Poales. They are similar adaptations to a similar life-style.
With around 780 genera and around 12,000 species,[3] the Poaceae is the fifth-largest plant family, after the Asteraceae, Orchidaceae, Fabaceae and Rubiaceae.[6]
The true grasses include cereals, bamboo and the grasses of lawns (turf) and grassland. Uses for graminoids include food (as grain, sprouted grain, shoots or rhizomes), drink (beer, whisky), pasture for livestock, thatching thatch, paper, fuel, clothing, insulation, construction, sports turf, basket weaving and many others.
Many grasses are short, but some grasses can grow tall, such as bamboo. Plants from the grass family can grow in many places and make grasslands, including areas which are very arid or cold. There are several other plants that look similar to grass and are referred to as such, but are not members of the grass family. These plants include rushes, reeds, papyrus and water chestnut. Seagrass is a monocot in the order Alismatales.
Grasses are an important food for many animals, such as deer, buffalo, cattle, mice, grasshoppers, caterpillars and many other grazers. Unlike other plants, grasses grow from the bottom, so when animals eat grass they usually do not destroy the part that grows.[7] This is a part of why the plants are successful. Without grass, soil may wash away into rivers (erosion)."

author: @zachwooddesigns
text: Honestly, first forray into the film representation of Madame Web that's different than the comic strip representation that is always shared and I'm for it. This looks like a decent flik with a managed budget telling a time travel story with an evil spider-man type villain. That's new and different in a live-action form. It's probably not going to blow me away like Infinity War but at least Sony is pumping out Spider-Man related movies with their copyrighted characters and trying. The best strategy the Sony universe can take is to reincorporate Andrew Garfield back into live-action to tie things together. They've played ball with the MCU with one of their variants. Sony's biggest crux is writing and I think they should work on that a little more since Venom 2. If they can fix that, I think they'll turn things around. Can't hate on the financial investment into their best characters no matter what.

author: @Dave2kool4skool
text:
I almost cried when Madame Web said

"As far back as I can remember, I always wanted to be a gangster.¬†To me, being a gangster was better than being President of the United States. Even before I first wandered into the cabstand for an afterschool job I knew I wanted to be a part of them. It was there that I knew that I belonged. To me, it meant being somebody in the neighborhood that was full of nobodies. They weren‚Äôt like anybody else. I mean, they did whatever they wanted. They double parked in front of a hydrant and nobody ever game them a ticket. In the summer when they played cards all night, nobody ever called the cops. Tuddy Cicero. Tuddy. Tuddy ran the cabstand in La Bella Vista Pizzeria and a few other places for his brother Paul who was the boss over everybody in the neighborhood. Paulie might have moved slow, but it was only because he didn‚Äôt have to move for anybody.

At first, my parents loved that I found a job across the street. My father, who was Irish, was sent to work at the age of eleven, and he liked that I got myself a job. He always said American kids were spoiled lazy.And my mother was happy after she found out that the Varios came from the same part of Sicily as she did. To my mother, it was the answer to her prayers.

I was the luckiest kid in the world. I could go anywhere. I could do anything. I knew everybody and everybody knew me. But it wasn‚Äôt too long before my parents changed their minds. For them, the cabstand was supposed to be a part-time job, but for me, it was full-time. People like my father could never understand, but I was a part of something. I belonged. I was treated like a grown-up. Every day I was learning to score. My father was always pissed off. He was pissed that he had to work so hard. He was pissed that he made such lousy money. Be was pissed that there were seven of us living in a tiny house. But after a while, he was mostly pissed that I hung around the cabstand. He said they were bums and that I was a bum. He said I was going to get into trouble. I used to say I was only running errands after school, but he knew better. He knew what went on at the cabstand and, every once in a while, usually after he got his load on, I had to take a beating. But by then, I didn‚Äôt care. No matter how many beatings I took, I wouldn‚Äôt listen to what he said. I don‚Äôt think I even heard him. The way I saw it, everybody has to take a beating some time.

That was it. No more letters from truant officers. No more letters from school. In fact, no more letters from anybody. How could I go back to school after that and pledge allegiance to the flag and sit through good government bullshit.

Hundreds of guys depended on Paulie and he got a piece of everything they made. It was tribute, just like the old country, except they were doing it in America. All they got from Paulie was protection from other guys looking to rip them off. That‚Äôs what it‚Äôs all about. That‚Äôs what the FBI can never understand, that what Paulie and the organization does is offer protection for people who can‚Äôt go to the cops. They‚Äôre like the police department for wiseguys.

People looked at me differently. They knew I was with somebody. I didn‚Äôt have to wait on line at the bakery on Sunday morning anymore for fresh bread. The owner knew who I was with, and he‚Äôd come from around the counter, no matter how many people were waiting. I was taken care of first. author: @zmanjz
text:
Hmmm... the precog/groundhog day plot device/ story mechanic seems very interesting and the main character seems well cast, BUT the glimpses of the other female spiderman-esque characters is a bit worrisome as they look lame. The diverse girl-power team-up, is a choice... but it implies a very limited number of potential storylines, limited writing range, and zero chance of romance; ala the terrible bomb "The 355".

(I remember Original spiderman 2002, the kiss between upside down Spiderman and Mary Jane was one of the most romantic scenes in a super hero movie ever. That moment is crystal clear in my memory nearly 20 years later.) So while this DOES have some story potential, I am worried about some big red flags of cringe .

author: @SageofStars
text:
Not to join the peanut gallery, but if you're gonna go vague powered dude that no one's ever heard of for our villain with a connection to the spider family...why not Judas Traveler? At least then it would be amusing, and an eight foot tall dude with white hair and a beard who can animorph into a hawk, control souls, and command space time to make carnage into a lawyer for one comic, would be a villain who could get stuff done, and fight a woman who's whole power set revolves around seeing the future.

Sims is...he's not that good. Zeke barely could fight a very sick Peter Parker most times, despite the Spider-Totem powers he had. Heck, Peter had to save HIM during at least one of their fights(Yes yes it was a 'test' of Peter being a hero, but it really didn't seem like he was any better in a fight next time either).

Anyway, still disappointed Marvel refuses to let Judas into any of these movies...this is not that I like the character, I just want to see him get the snot beat out of him.

text:
I love the part where Madame Web says:

"All right, let's do this one last time. My name is Cassandra Webb. I was drawned by a radioactive river, and for ten years I've been the one and only Madame Web. I'm pretty sure you know the rest. I saved a bunch of people, fell in love, saved the future, and then I saved the future again... and again and again and again. And I, uh... I did this... [movie]

We don't really talk about this. Look, I'm a comic book, I'm a cereal, did a Christian Grey album. I have an excellent theme song. And a so-so popsicle. I mean, I've looked worse. But after weberything, I still love being Madame Web. I mean, who wouldn't? So no matter how many hits I take, I always find a way to come back. Because the only thing standing between this future and oblivion is me. There's only one Madame Web. And you're looking at her."

'Nuff said.

author: @Luz4SiKio
text:
This trend of modern feminists imbuing every show/movie with toxic femininity has become a problem for us fantasy/sci- fans. And what makes it so much worse is that if we comment about it we're called misogynists. This needs to stop.
It's also so extremely hypocritical and devious of them. They have become the very thing they hated in men. The stories used to have great women and men as characters, not this all-woman casting and repeating theme of demeaning men that we've seen for years now. Equality would equally represent male and female, not one or the other. This trend is creating more cultural problems than helping.
Hollywood needs to stop lazily shoving their political crap into their productions, because it breaks all emersion and is creating more division and culture wars. Also, good writers with skill and care can put a parable that's uplifting for the world into a story and that still have a great plot, world building, and character development. This is just fan fiction surface level writing that uses virtue signaling to attack anyone who critiques it.

text:
Madame web should be an Older Woman, the actress picked does not work for this role and the dynamic their trying to achieve, but the casting for the other Spider-Women/Girls is good. I Kinda like they way they are handling her power but the decision to make Ezekiel sims when he is normally an ally but then again he has been a foe and this makes him more unique to these heroes. I'm more peeved tat she not an elderly woman as that could have been really cool, she could still be active, a seasoned heroin in a timeline where Peter doesnt exist and she's the OG spider-women but Ezekiel cripples her and blinds her causing her to adapt/learn with the young heroes she's mentoring, just a missed opportunity as we don't see elderly heroes and them taking on that mentorship.

But the QUALITY just look off, like low budget, fan filmy and that's really harsh i know but no hate to those who worked on this project but the fact this was shadow dropped to me seems like they just released it for the sake of doing so, but i'll give Sony credit and some props for actually believing in it, as we've seen with WB cancelling movies left and right like Batgirl, and Coyote v ACME.

Pro:
That first fight sequence looked good. I'm still a fan of the flipping camera in a fight trope.
At least they all look like they're enjoying themselves in this movie.
It's going to at least be better than Morbius. I'll take that as a win.

author: @DarthTingleBinks
text:
This looks even worse than the vignette did. Acting wise, anyway. Also, "My mom was researching Spiders," is such a dumb way to make the character related to spiders.

I do want to want to talk about something I've seen people say in the comments, though... None of you know what a fan film is. Because this does not look like one. It looks like a bad professional film, but it doesn't look pike a fan film. So let me educate you.

1. 'Fan film' doesn't denote or imply a low leve of quality. There are good fan films.
2. 'Professional film' doesn't denote or imply a highvlevel of quality. There are bad professional films.
3. Typically, the only difference between a fan film and a professional film is production budget. Fan films are more often than not cheaper than professional films, which may or may not be noticeable depending on how well the film was made.
4. If you're calling this a fan film because the acting is bad, then you're once again using the term 'fan film' to denote or imply a level lf quality lower than that of a 'professional film'. And again, neither term implies a level of quality in any way. Not in writing, not in acting, not in directing, not in cinematography, etc. The terms can usually be used to denote or imply a vast difference in budget. But not even that is certain as an expensive fan film can be as much as a cheap professional film.
5. The only thing you can say for certain is that fan films are made without the backing of any studio, whereas professional films are made with the backing of one or more studios.

So basically, anyone referring to this as a fan film is clearly retarded.
